{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e43751a7-65f3-435d-a103-15cbe3404624","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 which supports constructor injection for `TestContext`. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization, IAsyncCleanup\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Synchronous init via constructor (inject TestContext)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // sync setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async init (runs after constructor, before each test)\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup here (e.g., DB connections, HTTP clients)\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup (runs after each test)\n    public Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        // async teardown here\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsTrue(true);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection**: MSTest 3.x+ injects `TestContext` automatically via the constructor — no need for the property setter pattern.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`**: Implement for async setup that runs before each test method.\n- **`IAsyncCleanup`**: Implement for async teardown after each test.\n- The constructor handles synchronous setup; `InitializeAsync` handles anything requiring `await`.\n\nThis replaces the older `[TestInitialize]`/`[TestCleanup]` attribute approach while giving you both sync and async lifecycle hooks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"786be969-57a0-4821-86e7-813102c31ee1","outputTokens":397,"requestId":"E445:3A3321:1BC5823:1DC1363:6A02FB74"},"id":"2c9ee1b9-0a2a-4168-9912-dee8012dce53","timestamp":"2026-05-12T10:05:54.064Z","parentId":"d29cb294-65f3-4bdf-a619-2a0a5c4fde5f"}
